    <p>A number of student and scholarship tickets will be available to those who need them.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="team">
    <h2>Team</h2>
    <p>The core organising group is <a href="https://twitter.com/benschwarz">@benschwarz</a>, <a href="https://twitter.com/mobywhale">@mobywhale</a>, <a href="https://twitter.com/xzyfer">@xzyfer</a>, <a href="https://twitter.com/glenmaddern">@glenmaddern</a> and <a href="https://twitter.com/toolmantim">@toolmantim</a>. We’ve run community events all around Australia including JSConf, RubyConf, SydCSS and Rails&nbsp;Camp.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sponsorship">
    <h2>Sponsorship</h2>
    <p>We’re looking for fantastic companies to help make this event possible. If you think your company could help, please drop an email to <a href="mailto:sponsors@THISDOMAIN">sponsors@THISDOMAIN</a>.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="contact">
    <h2>Talk Proposals</h2>
    <p>There’ll be a number of slots open for talk proposals. We’ll announce shortly what the submission and selection process will be.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="spread-the-word">
    <h2>Spread the word</h2>
    <p>If you know someone that you’d like to be at the first CSSConf Australia, either to speak or just to hang out with, then let them know. If you don’t know anyone in particular, ask your Twitter peeps! Let’s try to get as many great people together as we can.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="contact">
    <h2>Code of Conduct</h2>
    <p>CSSConf Australia strives to be an inclusive, safe, accessible and fun event for everyone involved. It’s an important condition of participation that all organisers, sponsors and attendees follow the <a href="http://confcodeofconduct.com/">Conference Code of Conduct</a> at the conference and related events.</p>
  </section>

